Hello there!
Welcome to my mini project! The purpose of this project is to analyse the long term patterns of CO2 emission throughout 1959s to 1997 using Time Series model. Alongside reading this page, you can open RStudio and code along and try to experiment. Here, we will use some co2 after we a package, which are prophet that will help us model a time series model. Why do we use co2? co2 is the built-in dataset that is in R, which shows the CO2 concentration in atmosphere, in parts per million(ppm). If you run ‘?co2’ in R console, it will shows information of co2 dataset, if you are interested to know more.



The Usage of Prophet in Our Analysation


We use Prophet in this analysation because it is easy to use even for people without time series background to navigate! So don’t forgot to install and use your ‘prophet’ package, if you are coding along!


Plot of Carbon Emission in Atmosphere in par million(ppm)


Here is a simple graph where we will see the relationship of our two variables of the co2 datase. When you run the codes below, you will see a plot of Year(ds) and Carbon Emission in Atmosphere in par million(ppm)(y).


co2.df = data.frame(
  ds=zoo::as.yearmon(time(co2)), 
  y=co2)
m = prophet::prophet(co2.df, weekly.seasonality = TRUE, daily.seasonality = TRUE)
f = prophet::make_future_dataframe(m, periods=8, freq="quarter")
p = predict(m, f)
plot(m,p)


Observing our plot, we can see an overall upward trend for the overall graph from the year 1959 to 1997. But, if we look closer to the graph, we can see the zig-zags, where the pattern oscillates up and down, around 10 times per 10 year. This might be due to factors such as seasons where the temperature increase and decreases throughout the whole year. Another interesting observation that I saw is after the year of 1997, there’s some forecasting of the carbon emission until the year of 2000(The blue straight line). It’s interesting to see that the model predict the same pattern for the next few years. But, how about next 20 years? Will the forecasting predicts the carbon emission to keep on rising? Perhaps we can run a regression analysis to observe is model works for the co2 dataset we’re currently using, plus a forecast to predict future carbon emission.


Regression Analysis


Next, we will run some regression analysis and we will discuss through our results at the end. Some of the regression that will be discussed would be Residuals versus Fitted, Q-Q Residuals, Scale-Location and Residuals Versus Leverage. 

lm_model <- lm(y ~ ds, data = co2.df)
plot(lm_model)


Discussion


  1. Residuals vs Fitted Plot
    The result of residual analysis, we can observe the data are roughly around the residual line of 0. As a result, we can say that the relationship is linear. As for outliers, we have point 5, 17 and 214 are a bit too far from the red residual line.
  2. Q-Q Residuals
    The result of our Q-Q plot shows that most of our datapoins falls above the 45 degree line, which means the data are linearly distributed. However, there are a few outliers on top and bottom of the plot. Hence, we have to look at other
  3. Scale-Location
    The plot looks randomly scattered all over the graph and it’s a good sign. Moreover, no residuals stands out from the scatter of plot.
  4. Residuals vs Leverage
    Based on the observation of Residuals vs Leverage, there is no outlying values on top right or bottom right of the plot, indicating that no influential cases.


Forecasting CO2 Emissions in the Future


Next, we will look on forecast of carbon emission in the future. when we run the code for period 100, we will get the graph below.

m = prophet::prophet(co2.df, weekly.seasonality = TRUE, daily.seasonality = TRUE)
f = prophet::make_future_dataframe(m, periods=50, freq="quarter")
p = predict(m, f)
plot(m,p)


m = prophet::prophet(co2.df, weekly.seasonality = TRUE, daily.seasonality = TRUE)
f = prophet::make_future_dataframe(m, periods=100, freq="quarter")
p = predict(m, f)
plot(m,p)


Well, what do we observe here in the plot? What are the differences in these two plots above?
In the first plot, we forecast a 10 year prediction of carbon emission, while the second forecast is for about 20 years. Overall, after the year 1997, we can observe that the oscillation patterns are still constant through out the years, while the overall trend will keep on increasing every year until the year after 2020. There is some highlighted parts in blue, where the data is predicted to fall under them, if the emission are increasing or decreasing. So, what will happen if we change the period to less than 50, or more 100? What do you think the observation will looks like?

Well, at the end of the day, reality is the one that matters. Hence, does this forecast reflect the reality? What is the limitation of this forecast?


Reflection


Overall, we can conclude that dataset co2 are showing a positive correlation between years and CO2 emission throughout the years, supported with regression analysis that shows a positive result of the data fits the model. Next, how about our forecast? Does the result from our forecast reflect the reality? Comparing the real world and our forecast, the forecast definitely cannot predict any catasthrope events that will be happening in the world. In 2019-2020, the carbon emission in real world drastically decrease due to Covid-19 outbreak. Due to restriction in movement from a place to another, cars and flights CO2 emission are very little compared to before the outbreaks happen. Hence, we can categorise this as time series model limitations. Overall, this model here are very interesting to look at how carbon emission has been increasing since the 1970s and would probably still increase through the years. This is very important as we need to learn what, how and when will affect our earth, as this is our ultimate home. In the future, I am more interested to further this analysation and take more factors into consideration, and to investigate if other factors might increase CO2 emission in the earth.
